Barack Obama will receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth president of the United States.
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo for 26 hours to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
He will receive a diploma, a medal and a check for $1.4 million for outstanding efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The head of the White House will fly to the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife Michelle and he will be busy.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of the committee, which selected him from 172 people and 33 organizations in October.
The presidential couple is then scheduled to meet with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will receive a prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to win the award, but only the third to win it in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will speak about the Afghan war when accepting the award.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he realizes that he is accepting the prize as the president who is currently at war in two countries.
He increased the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which he will not forget to highlight any of his critics.
During the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for 10 million Swedish kronor (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to give them for charitable purposes, but has not yet decided on a specific charity.
A busy program will then take the president and his wife to a banquet, where, in addition to the Norwegian king and queen, there will also be a prime minister and another 250 invited guests.
From the start, Obama has been very cautious about prices.
He said, for example, that he felt he did not deserve it.
He also reiterated several times that this is not just a prize for him, but for all those who strive for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said it was "a call to action".
