Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is comical how schoolboyly Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor, whom he considered the dumbest, on the Afghan issue.
When he finally sweated out his much-anticipated Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he copied it through a copy machine from Bush’s Iraq script three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate to even use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement as the title of his own declaration: "A New Way Forward".
Three years ago, he criticized Bush’s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to civil war-torn Iraq as “irresponsible and ultimately catastrophic.”
But the months that followed showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field commanders, was the only one that was so possible and so successful that there is no talk about Iraq in news programs today.
It did not improve Bush’s reputation, but it did objectively leave his successor with a far more grateful starting point than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will happen again.
He was once again asked by field commanders to increase his military contingent, especially by the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the hesitant gunmen in the White House, despite his subordination habits.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but did not fall for anything better, so at least he cheated the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to squeeze the promise of another 5,000 out of Europe, even though he himself had originally counted at least 10.
The most problematic part of Obama’s strategy seems to be his intention to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in just 18 months, and to end the process in three years.
Many doubt that the half-hearted increase will give the same fruits as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well-ordered, its leaders honoring the agreements.
The Afghan situation is marked by the opposite sign - no one can be relied on and no agreements are respected.
Under these conditions, Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing their masters every day, are preparing poorly.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain only a Potemkin village, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult due to the lack of clarity of the circumstances, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the construction of an "actionable state", which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, does not seem very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is striking with its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of an explosion.
Only a truly romantic soul, untouched by reality, can believe that soldiers sent into the turmoil for the purpose of "coming home soon" will cause a miracle here.
Politically, the date of the withdrawal is a sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will view it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is close to minus.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically interfering with the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the United States will be faced with the difficult question of whether or not to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will need to be answered just as Obama says America is about to pull out of Afghanistan.
Any such solution, however, will also mark a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only sticking point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left before the presidential election, so there is still enough time to come up with another strategy if this turns out to be a total flop.
