Czech discovery: a substance that works even on 'hardy' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already acquired immunity against drugs.
This fact in some cases outweighs the fact that the compound does not act on the common variant of the virus as much as some already available drugs.
AIDS cannot be cured.
However, patients can significantly extend the life of a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of virus proliferation results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the University of Chemistry and Technology Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metallocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metal-carborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come up with new ‘enhanced’ compounds prepared based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Traitorous and resilient virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV cleavage, no mature infectious viral particles would arise.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, researchers describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain that is further systematically altered.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of agents against HIV protease was tested in a test tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of metallocarborans on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modifications, make metal carborans interesting compounds for further research aimed at the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
