We didn’t keep anything for others, says Wang, 31, a human resources administrator who has an 8-month-old son.
China's more than 30-year-old policy of having only one child has been introduced, creating two generations of only notoriously cuddled and clumsy children, affectionately dubbed "little emperors", the country is threatened by a population crisis.
The average birth rate fell to 1.8 children per couple, compared to six before politics went into effect, according to UN figures.
Population distribution, where the population aged 60 and above is projected to grow tumultuously from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050, is far above the overall average of around 20 percent.
