Gradual reassurance
As inserted into the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is arguably the most controversial mandate ever introduced under Communist Party rule to this day.
The couples who violated the policy faced enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some areas -- and discrimination at work.
China's official sites have pursued policies that have helped the country prevent critical exploitation of natural resources, while human rights defenders have been condemned in pursuing policies.
In rural areas, some officials forced pregnant women to abort their second child.
In addition, many couples have had sexist selective abortions, resulting in unnaturally high male-to-female ratios.
In recent years, population officials have been progressively more lenient in their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they generally allowed exceptions - including city dwellers, members of national minorities, and cases where a man and a woman were only children - and in 2007 they relaxed the diction of their hard-line slogans.
