The UN group outlined a plan to reduce emissions.
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by far-reaching unruly attitudes and mutual defamation -- focused once again on Friday to release a document proposing ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden in the near future.
The text, which can provide a starting point for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, highlights the remaining obstacles as well as illuminating the way forward.
But there has been significant progress in negotiations that have taken place at the wrong time with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Created by the UN ad hoc working group, this text subtly states how much money rich countries should provide to the poor to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a range of choices for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies to limit their carbon output, and what should be the upper limit on the global temperature rise that policymakers will still be able to tolerate.
This gives the process a great deal of flexibility, says John Coequyt, executive director of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, abbreviated from 180 pages of text from the meeting to focus on what the top climate official at the UN, Yvo de Boer, described as a "big picture".
It outlines a possible agreement in which industrial nations could collectively limit their emissions to 25 to 45 percent by 1990 levels, while major developing countries could reduce their emissions to 15 to 30 percent during that period.
Together, the countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
On Friday, the European Union urgently discussed a pledge to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to climate change -- from managing floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
However, Friday still featured the same kind of verbal fireworks that prevailed in last week’s interviews.
U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern has rejected a speech calling for a binding cut in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries compared to volunteering for major emerging economies if not funded by the developed world.
