Stern made the comment an hour after China's deputy foreign minister He Yafei told the US chief climate negotiator that either a lack of "common sense" or "extraordinary irresponsibility" had led to the announcement earlier in the week that the United States would not help China financially to deal with global warming.
With the future of the world’s major economic powers at stake, tensions have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrialized world and emerging economies.
The current struggle is mostly for the preservation of individual economies rather than the preservation of the planet, between China and the United States to meet their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that the world’s two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperative to take stronger action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate to Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that major powers are fighting over who should bear the cost of reducing greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries have become much more aggressive in finding ways to zak preventing large issuers responsibly in their actions.
It’s clearly a game about the new economic hegemony being developed, said Ulate, who also serves as regional advisor on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for international nature conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to climate change have indicated that they would like to continue enforcing the legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but a majority of the main participants said that the best outcome of the talks would be a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, created a 24-page draft deal last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led the international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said enforcement by small island nations "has raised a political tug over the entire political process" partly because they are now united and are demanding action from growing economies such as China and India.
The negotiations sparked a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the remaining issues before heads of government would contest the deal.
High-ranking officials such as India’s environment minister, Jairam Ramesh, and China’s deputy minister stepped off planes and ran through the halls of the Bella Center to closed doors meetings and new conferences so they could set claims that will be assessed next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering - with 13,000 people moving daily from and to the convention center, guitar-playing activists staging ironic spectacles at night about the countries they thought they had sent, and hand-to-hand submissions on paper rather than e-mail - controlled by challenge.
The intensity is only a superstructure: almost all key ministers were present in Copenhagen, and earlier in the middle of 60 heads of state.
We have come into high categories, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Deputy Minister for Global Policy in International Nature Conservation.
Here come the heavy weights.
