The country's first high-speed passenger train reaches 140 miles per hour and flies from Ashford, Kent to London's St Pancras, covering a distance of 58 miles in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, then joined Mrs Kelly Holmes and boarded the first high-speed passenger train outside London.
It hopes the new service will eventually connect Britain with an international network of fast, reliable trains and connect the large conurbations of Midland, North and Scotland with London.
Neglected stagnant waters should cut passenger and business travel times, and switching from aircraft and cars to rail could reduce carbon emissions and eliminate congestion on the roads.
In theory, the three main political parties have allowed themselves to be won over for this vision.
