Abkhazia elected its president on Saturday, about a year after Moscow recognized the pro-Russian separatist territory as independent from Georgia, while Tbilisi declared the move a “farce.”
About 131,000 people were invited to participate in these first elections after the Russo-Georgian War of August 2008 for control of South Ossetia, another former Georgian territory recognized by Russia.
Polling stations closed at 17:00 GMT.
According to officials of the Abkhazian Electoral Commission, the turnout was 58% a few hours before the polling stations closed.
The first preliminary results should be announced on the night of Saturday to Sunday.
All five candidates, including incumbent President Sergei Bagapsh, categorically reject the idea of merging with Georgia, which condemned the election.
This election is a farce.
On the other hand, Georgian President Mikhail Saakashvili "regrets that Abkhazia has completely fallen into Russian domination," said his spokesman, Manana Manjgaladze.
Apart from Russia, only Nicaragua and Venezuela have recognized the independence of this territory with 216,000 inhabitants, while the rest of the world considers it part of Georgia, which was illegally occupied by Russian troops.
After separation from Georgia, after the 1992-1993 conflict that killed several thousand people, Abkhazia is trying to show through elections that it is ready to return to international politics.
This process is one of the stages of our new life, a new era of our independent state, said Kvarčija Světlanová, a 54-year-old historian who also admitted that she voted for President Bagapse.
