The UDF is raising the tone and calling on the Nouveau Centre to no longer use their acronym.
The UDF, controlled by MoDemFrancois Bayrou, responded on Friday to an attempt by Nouveau Centre party president Hervé Morin to appropriate the acronyms of the former Giscard party, saying it must not use the abbreviation in any media under threat of criminal prosecution.
Hervé Morin publicly announced his intention to usurp the UDF acronym, saying that Francois Bayrou did not deserve to carry her legacy after shaking the left's hand.
The Defense Minister, whose party is a partner of the UMP, planned to confirm this strategy on Saturday in front of the National Council of the Nouveau Centre (NC) movement.
This move gained the support of Hervé de Charetto, a former MP now for NC, who claims ownership of the UDF brand because he first registered it with the National Institute of Industrial Property (l'Institut national de la propriété industrielle) in 2004.
But on Friday night, a committee of the UDF Association, run by friends of Francois Bayrou, who have no intention of being expropriated, stepped out of its silence and made a formal request to both the minister and MPs to stop using the shortcut and hand back ownership of the trademark, under threat of criminal prosecution.
In recent days, you have increased the worrying statements that you will propose to your political movement to retake the UDF acronym, writes the Association in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 committee members, such as Francois Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez of the MoDem party or Senator Jean Arthuis of the Alliance centriste.
At the same time, you considered it appropriate to put the name +Nouveau centre+ on your promotional materials and on the welcome page of your movement, with the slogan +UDF today+, the signatories of the letter also state.
As you are aware, you have no right to use this abbreviation, the UDF committee, which requests the NC movement "immediately remove all references to the UDF name from all promotional materials including (its) website".
At the same time, he asks Hervé de Charette "to hand over the ownership of the trademark to the legitimate owners".
If you fail to do so, we will go to the courts to ensure that the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members are respected.
In their letter, they state that the UDF "is a full-fledged political movement since 1978" and recall that Mr. Morin and his friends "elected" to leave in 2007 "to form a competitive movement, as others did in 2002, to establish the UMP.
According to them, the Nouveau Centre movement has no right to use the abbreviation UDF (Union pour la démocratie francaise).
At the same time, they recall that the last UDF Congress voted in 2007 to join the MoDem for three years and to form a committee charged with defending the "moral and material interests" of the association founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the committee continues, "when he registered the trademark", he was "not a member of the UDF for three years" but a UMP.
In a scandalous and fraudulent manner, he used non-existent registration acronyms to do so on his own account.
This indiscretion is beginning to turn into a crime, they claim, and then ironically comment on NC's strategy: "It seems to us that, both in politics and in everyday life, it is more valuable to make a name for ourselves than to step out of anonymity by fraudulently adopting a name to which we have no right".
The case of Liliane Bettencourt : Francois-Marie Banier will be tried for abuse of a state of weakness.
A court in Nanterre decided on Friday to try artist Francois-Marie Banier and decide whether he used the state of weakness of the 80-year-old billionaire to deprive her of part of her fortune, according to her daughter Liliane Bettencourt.
The photographer (62 years old), known for his photographs of famous people, will be tried on April 15 and 16, 2010 for abuse of a state of weakness, a crime for which a penalty of a maximum of 3 years and a fine of 375,000 euros is imposed.
The ruling confirms that there will indeed be a trial in what could be called the family saga of one of the wealthiest families in France, in which a mother and daughter are attacking each other and fighting over the management of L’Oréal’s beauty empire.
However, the 15th Criminal Court also ordered a medical examination of 87-year-old Liliana Bettencourt, which should be conducted by a college of three doctors.
The heiress and chief shareholder of L’Oréal has always refused to undergo such an investigation, certainly not under the conditions offered by the Nanterre prosecutor’s office during the investigation.
The doctors, who will be elected on Friday, should prepare a report by March 10, 2010, and at the same time give a statement as to whether Liliana Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness, and in which period.
I think he's going to do it.
I'll talk to her about it," Bettencourt's attorney, Georges Kiejman, said after the hearing.
As for the lawyer, Francois Bettencourt-Meyers, Olivier Metzner, he welcomed the court's decision.
It is excellent news(...). Expertise will show that with this old lady in need of protection, he manipulated (M. Banier), confirmed.
It has been two years since Liliana Bettencourt’s only daughter launched a criminal case against Francois-Marie Banier, a photographer and omniscientist whom she blames for years of exploiting her mother’s state of weakness in order to win a billion euros as a gift in the form of checks, life insurance contracts, or master paintings.
Liliane Bettencourt has always denied being manipulated by a photographer she considers to be a long-term friend.
While the court had to assess the merits of Mrs Bettencourt-Meyers' lawsuit, Friday's barrister's speech at times turned into a family hour of truth.
Liliana Bettencourt's lawyer presented three letters that his client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) had sent to her notary, in which she expressed her disbelief towards Fran ois Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In a 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt, according to the attorney, adds, "you could explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier for fifteen years once or twice a day.
Since she got married, I've never been able to talk to Francoise."
The Nanterre prosecutor’s office again found that the applicant’s conduct was not warranted, all the more so since a guardian judge had recently rejected her application to initiate proceedings to grant legal protection to her mother.
