The Turkish justice system has dissolved for the Kurdish side and this decision has serious consequences.
Turkey's Constitutional Court on Friday ruled to abolish the country's main pro-Kurdish party, prompting protest demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the country's south-east and in Istanbul.
This decision can greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to extend a friendly hand to the Kurdish community and try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it became "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Supreme Court Chief Justice Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of negotiations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, when a majority-seven votes were needed to dissolve the party, Kilic said, adding that 37 party cadres including its president Ahmet Turek and MP Aysela Tugluk were banned from participating in political life for five years.
