Cradle of Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: The animal, two meters long and 1.50 meters high, ran on two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short forelimbs with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues write in Thursday’s issue of the journal Science that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these features.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry region of the supercontinent Pangaea.
Tawa is opening a new window to an earlier evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about kinship relationships, expansion, and the traits of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavations at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, unprecedented for triassic deposits, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The discovery confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god Hopi Indians.
It is an unusual find for Sterling Nesbitt: "The fossils of the Triassic dinosaurs are very rare, mostly only single fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm unreservedly.
This finding is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the assignment of pradinosaurs is mostly questionable.
Experts discuss, for example, when lizards split into three most important development lines: carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor, and also birds, "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and herbivores Ornithopschia, which included, for example, species of Ornithops.
Tawa hallae is the original terapod after an analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, researchers have found evidence of air sacs that even the descendants of theropods have birds.
Air sacs make the breathing of birds more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since a related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation has probably created a common ancestor of the two groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists have deduced that lizards appeared there for the first time.
According to this, the three lines of development soon split and spread from South America to all the continents, which at that time, as a supercontinent of Pangaea, formed a uniform earth mass.
The team found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related, theropods along with Tawa hallae.
The three cannot come from one common, immigrant ancestor, scientists argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the scientific study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
One even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says the Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His conjecture could put together a distorted picture, as very many primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved in South America, while they are rarely found on other continents.
How dinosaurs proved that they evolved from a relatively rare sideline of the reptilian genus to the ruling vertebrates on earth during the Earth's Middle Ages remains a riddle.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their living space with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and flying lizards, and countless other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species developed, while relatives died out and the interface of the Triassic and Jurassic.
The success story didn’t last forever.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the reptiles did not.
Or maybe the dinosaurs adapted better, so they could push out the competition.
But the success story didn’t last forever.
150 million years later, the impact of the meteorite helped another group of animals, which also evolved into the Triassic and has lived in the shade ever since: mammals.
