Worlds of Dreams
Some see images in their waking state and hear voices that others cannot see or hear.
It is not just the mentally ill or drugged that blur the lines between imagination and reality.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything is fine.
If we lie with our eyes closed in our dark room, we may surround ourselves with the wildest fantasies and fanciful mirages.
But in today’s Western world, those who experience dream states, see and hear things that others don’t see or hear, are usually considered crazy or drug addicts, or at least odd.
However, such images and voices do not arise only in the mentally ill or in drug intoxication.
The same neuronal processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings, or write novels make sure that the boundaries between dream, imagination, and reality flow.
Dreams of altered state of consciousness can occur in various forms, at best we call them visions, in worse delusions.
Although the initiator and effect may vary, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of New-Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the shamanic states of delirium, psychosis, and hallucination can be derived from similar processes.
Hallucinations or visions occur when the balance of the brain's neuronal transmitters - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin, and acetylcholine - is derailed, and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusions occur very often in schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over it.
The link between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle saw hallucinations as a form of waking dream, and Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychology, stated in 1861 that "there was a great similarity between delirium and dream states"; for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the nonsense, mirages, deceiving of the senses".
It's fall 2001, Henning T. is turning into a comic book character.
His body is two-dimensional and brightly colored.
Gravity has no power over it, it hovers at the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him winged devilish figures with blood-red grimaces, valuing teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy, fiery boots, throw him against walls, feel pain all over his body.
Loud, evil voices threaten from the walls and from the radio.
He can no longer stand the voices that insult and insult him.
Henning T. rips two cables out of the stereo, knots them into a loop, and fastens it to a hook on the ceiling.
He stands on one speaker and puts the loop around his neck.
He jumps.
Loop's loose.
Learn, shout chorus voices ripping his eardrums, "go to the clinic and get treated!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
LSD has been triggered.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective paranoid psychosis, in addition, he is manic-depressive, taking drugs for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He's learned to live with his illness, he's been married for three years.
In psychosis, I experienced the worst fears and deepest doubts, he says.
Ghosts are a terrible reality.
About one percent of people get schizophrenia at least once in their lives, in psychiatric clinics it is the second most frequently treated disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, the sufferers can no longer distinguish the inner and outer worlds, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship illusions or the illusion of persecution.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices - voices that command, comment or conduct dialogues.
Optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The sufferer is unable to distinguish the important from the unimportant, the brain cannot filter out the disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, psychosis opens the floodgates to thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the General Psychiatry Clinic of the University Clinic in Heidelberg.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, becomes, like in a dream, overwhelmed by events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is usually not possible, ghosts are a terrible reality, awakening is impossible.
Experience a hallucination once in a lifetime
Other than in a dream, Fuchss says, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality, which one perceives in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience occurs in a real framework.
Scientists are still puzzled as to why exactly our brains are doing such flips.
Emergencies can lead anyone to lose touch with reality in the short term, Fuchs says.
But not everyone develops into a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists believe that people with disabilities have minimal brain damage.
We believe that early in development, there will be damage to the neuronal maturation of the brain, for example, by the mother's viral diseases during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
However, it remains a puzzle as to how the neuronal system malfunctions, which has not manifested itself for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis, if there is a disposition for it.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis, as they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brain breaks down
The crazy thing is that psychotronics suffer from their hallucinations, and in order to get rid of them, they swallow expensive drugs, others give money for drugs in order to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of L beck.
Whether we perceive delusions as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions for ten years, last year he interpreted his results in the book "Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf" (Unreal world in our head).
Hallucinations are typical accompanying phenomena of psychoses, but also surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to psychological disorders such as borderline personality or depression, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's or brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brain of a healthy person hallucinates under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of the contents of thoughts that are normally repressed.
They arise when the parts of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are too active or too little repressed; when our brain becomes sagging, or when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also withdrawal of stimuli, stress, worries about love or other exceptional conditions.
In more recent studies, up to a third of those surveyed reported experiencing hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends a grammar school there.
A perfectly normal girl, actually.
If it wasn't for the shapes and the voices.
During breaks, she may be approached by a long-haired, dark-haired smoothie.
When he answers, her classmates look at her with surprise - no one but her sees and hears this boy.
This shy girl is considered a uptight dreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't eat, she knows that.
He's awake, he can hear and see the boy, just like he can hear and see the girl sitting next to him in the desk.
He may even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling. She likes the boy.
Am I crazy? he sometimes asks.
But he knows that this boy and other mirages are not real and will disappear again.
At night, the signs are rather dismal.
They are often a burden.
When he sits in the classroom, he cannot watch the lessons many times, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is the new classmate, but he explains to everyone else in a clear and visible way on the board of mathematical equations.
At night the appearances are rather disheartening.
When she waits in her dark room for a sleep that comes rarely and too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or asleep, whether the images she sees, grimaces, or a girl with bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, arise in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, he's yelling at the characters.
She doesn't tell her parents and friends about it, they'd think she's crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she has not gone crazy.
Imagination is also an art of despair.
If someone is socially isolated or deprived of stimulation, they are likely to hallucinate, Kasten says.
I think the brain doesn't have enough work to do its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she’d been calling her dad since she thought for herself was not her own father.
Because in visual and acoustic hallucinations the same brain regions are active, which also process real perceptions and sounds, it is difficult for those affected, like Sarah K., to distinguish between delusion and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, and reality is also displayed there.
Hallucinations are also images that cause the brain to develop, which is why it feels so real.”
Night dreams are also evaluated by Kasten as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations in healthy people are not fundamentally different from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore advises her patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
The Borderline Between Dream and Hallucination
Unfortunately, in our world, the imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor in Heidelberg and chief physician at the Psychiatric and Psychotherapy Clinic of the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Dusseldorf.
Psychosis is a difficult, painful disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - the mirage is also an art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard examined the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of altered consciousness to dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictitious dreams that the affected person considers to be real and cannot even distinguish them from the waking state.
Oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience full consciousness motor paralysis.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and himself, perhaps by the continued, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situations with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between a dream and a hallucination.
Because in reality it is not possible to manage a situation, there will be a change of worlds, but the real situation becomes present into the imagination.
An intense form of sensory support and sensory transference in an unbearable situation that allows humans to move into loss of consciousness in an instant.
Everything is real, even later in the memories
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" (The Exchange of the Heart) as a soul rescue action.
He was 49 years old when, after heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, his consciousness went on a several-day journey while his body lay motionless in an intensive care unit.
Claussen plunges into the world he has created, visiting alien times and places: He becomes an old man confined to his bed, in a train sanatorium, a robot guarding his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility, which produces narcotics from blood.
On a motorbike, a Greek kidnaps him to his home country, surfs a firn in the Alps on a hospital bed, and meets a Korean mobster.
It sinks completely into imaginary events, everything is real, even later in memories.
These inner paths are fundamentally different for Claussen from any dream.
The dream is a different state, it describes your experience.
In contrast to dreams, the memories of those mental journeys are still clear years later and in non-essential details.
Even clearer and more intense than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other true experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychoses, hallucinations and drug intoxication show how fragile our inner images of external reality are even in the waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, Kasten summarizes, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality."
A fact that can also be enriching.
