75% of working mothers have maternity-related work problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and career of Spanish women', carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The study involved 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75, and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labor market because of motherhood.
The study highlights that, at the start of cohabitation, there are many differences of opinion about the number of children, depending on whether they work or not, as well as the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with a partner earlier, give birth to their first child earlier, and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable jobs, especially in the public sector, postpone cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer children.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with a stable job have their first child on average 3.7 years after the start of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 for women who have devoted a greater part of their lives to achieving a stable job and have therefore had to postpone cohabitation and the arrival of children.
The type of occupation also has a strong influence on motherhood, although less influence on the time of starting a life with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage andthe birth of a child is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at 25.1 and 32.1, respectively.
“There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with primary education get married and give birth to their first child before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education do the opposite, preferring to get a stable job, before getting married and having their first child,” Delgado said.
