Auxiliary system for handbrake is already mandatory equipment.
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock braking system, it will also be with ESP stability control, auxiliary handbrake systems, all this will become mandatory equipment for European cars.
In fact, it already forms part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while the others are subject to a deadline of February 2011.
The measures put in place in the EU aim to increase pedestrian protection, while working in a way that can help prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary handbrake system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects after the driver steps down.
However, it is not always possible to maintain this pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by automotive parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers who have an accident did not brake before a collision, and half of them did not fully use the force of the brake.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study conducted in the EU alone, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of device, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related fatalities could be avoided annually.
The reduction in this number will be even more noticeable - according to calculations would avoid one in four accidents affecting people - after the introduction of so-called intelligent hand brake systems.
In this case, the vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) detects obstacles and reports them to the driver, in addition to light braking.
If the driver responds, it will help to increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even when a collision cannot be avoided, the device will hit the brake as hard as possible and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
